<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
  Multiple agent sessions share <strong>one working tree</strong> in this repo. The whole-repo gate
  (<code>check:standards</code>) exits non-zero on <em>any</em> error and has no notion of <em>whose</em>
  change a violation belongs to — so a concurrent session's in-flight file reds <em>your</em> gate run,
  even though the breakage isn't yours. The standing rule says to step over a purely-external red, but
  the triage is manual today (<code>git status</code> + grep the error lines). This survey grounds
  <a href="/backlog/949-make-the-backlog-gate-attribute-violations-so-a-concurrent-s/">backlog&nbsp;#949</a>:
  how should the gate attribute violations to their owning work so that only <em>your</em> set blocks you?
</p>

<h3>Prior art surveyed</h3>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Nx <code>affected</code>.</strong> Git computes changed files against a <em>base ref</em>
    (default the main branch), the project graph expands them to affected projects, and tasks run only on
    that subset; base/head are explicit (<code>--base=main~1 --head=HEAD</code>) with a <code>--files</code>
    override. The canonical "scope CI to the changeset" pattern — but it assumes a <em>single actor against
    a clean base ref</em>.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>reviewdog <code>-filter-mode</code>.</strong> <code>added</code> (default; added/modified
    lines only), <code>diff_context</code>, <code>file</code> (whole file for any changed file), and
    <code>nofilter</code>. The linter still scans everything; findings are <em>filtered</em> to the diff
    before they fail or comment. <code>file</code> mode is the granularity #949 wants — a finding in a file
    you touched is yours.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Android Lint baseline / betterer.</strong> Snapshot current violations into a baseline file;
    later runs report <em>only new</em> issues. A <em>temporal</em> ratchet over legacy debt — separates
    old-vs-new in time, globally, not mine-vs-theirs by owner.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>lint-staged.</strong> Run linters only over git-staged paths — the per-commit changed set.
    Single-actor, clean-base assumption again.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>CODEOWNERS.</strong> A declared <em>path&nbsp;→&nbsp;owner</em> map — the "manifest" family of
    attribution: explicit and durable, but declared rather than derived, so it drifts from reality.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>git worktrees / per-branch isolation.</strong> Give each actor its own checkout against a
    clean base; then naive whole-repo gating already sees only that actor's work. The structural
    alternative that makes the single-actor tooling above simply apply.
  </li>
</ul>

<h3>The load-bearing mismatch</h3>
<p>
  Every "changed-files" tool above assumes <strong>one actor working against a clean base ref</strong>, so
  <code>git diff</code> vs <code>HEAD</code> <em>is</em> "my change." Our problem is the inverse:
  <strong>N actors sharing one dirty working tree with no per-actor branch</strong>, where
  <code>git diff</code> vs <code>HEAD</code> yields the <em>union</em> of everyone's edits — exactly the
  over-attribution we're undoing. Recovering "mine specifically" needs extra per-session state that
  single-actor tooling never carries (a per-session baseline snapshot, a declared manifest, or a session
  file-claim registry) — <em>or</em> the structural fix of isolating each session into its own worktree so
  a clean base re-appears.
</p>

<h3>What this hands the decision</h3>
<p>
  Three forks. <strong>Fork&nbsp;1 (strategy):</strong> attribute in-gate vs isolate sessions into git
  worktrees — recommend in-gate attribution (preserves the shared-tree + running-dev-server + commit-to-
  <code>main</code> workflow; isolation is the heavier escalation). <strong>Fork&nbsp;2 (signal):</strong>
  a per-session git baseline snapshot taken at <code>claim</code> (derived, not declared, fails safe) vs a
  declared frontmatter manifest vs a session file-claim registry extending <code>reservations.json</code>.
  <strong>Fork&nbsp;3 (behavior):</strong> a <code>--scope</code> filter mode (exit non-zero only on
  in-scope errors, default whole-repo run unchanged) vs a baseline ratchet (wrong axis — temporal, not
  by-owner) vs annotate-only (doesn't change the exit, so doesn't meet the ask). <code>check:health</code>
  reuses the scope mode keyed directly on item-id since its findings already carry one. Full grounding in
  <code>reports/2026-06-18-gate-violation-attribution.md</code>.
</p>
